 for bestpractices and # Dashboard

## Overview
Create the primary logged-in Dashboard for parents. This page surfaces recent studies, a child progress summary, a quick-create CTA to start new studies, and AI-generated recommended study suggestions. The UI must be visually friendly, accessible, and consistent with a playful, child-friendly design system. All data handling must be robust against null/undefined values and guarded against non-array results. The implementation should be modular, testable, and align with the Supabase-null-safety and React best practices described in the project’s mandatory coding standards.

## Page Description (Full Detail)
What this page is:
- The Dashboard is the main landing page after login. It presents a snapshot of the child’s learning activity and study-building capabilities, including:
  - Recent Studies: a list/grid of studies saved by the parent, with quick actions (Open, Duplicate, Share, Export).
  - Child Progress Summary: one or more progress overview cards showing progress percentage, current streak, and recency of activity for each child.
  - Quick Create Card: a prominent card to launch the study-creation wizard, with options to use uploaded teacher materials or start from a template.
  - Recommended Studies: AI-generated suggestions tailored to upcoming tests or teacher notes from uploaded documents, with actions to save, view, or start.
  - Top Navigation: global nav with logo, search, notifications, profile menu, and a prominent Create Study CTA.
  - Footer/Help: minimal help widget and link to Help pages if applicable.
- Goals:
  - Provide a concise, actionable overview of the child’s learning trajectory.
  - Enable rapid creation of new studies from templates or uploaded materials.
  - Personalize recommendations to encourage engagement and timely study planning.
- Connected features:
  - Study creation workflow (wizard), study saving/organization, duplication, sharing, exporting.
  - AI-powered recommendations based on uploaded docs and upcoming assessments (data sourced from user-provided materials; no external APIs required).
- UI elements and visual guidance:
  - Top navigation with a clear Create Study call-to-action.
  - Progress overview cards with numeric progress, streak indicators, and recency.
  - Responsive grid layouts that gracefully adapt to tablets and desktops; stacked on smaller viewports.
  - Card styles: soft rounded corners, gentle shadows, pastel backgrounds, and decorative illustrations.
  - Data visualization: simple charts or progress callouts with pastel color fills and minimal gridlines.
  - Interactive elements: hover/press states for clarity and delight, accessible focus states.
- API integrations:
  - No external API integrations required; all data sources are within the app or Supabase. Ensure flows gracefully handle empty states and data absence.

## Components to Build
- DashboardShell
  - Layout wrapper with header, content area, and responsive grid regions.
- TopNav
  - Global navigation with logo, search, notifications, profile menu, and a primary Create Study CTA.
- ProgressOverviewGrid
  - A responsive grid/cards for each child showing: total progress %, current streak, last activity timestamp, and a mini sparkline or icon.
  - Data sources: child records, progress metrics.
- RecentStudiesList
  - Card or list view of recent studies with actions: Open, Duplicate, Share, Export.
  - Each item must guard against non-array data and null results.
- QuickCreateCard
  - Card that triggers Study Wizard start; includes two action buttons:
    - Use uploaded teacher materials
    - Start from template
- RecommendedStudiesCarousel
  - Horizontally scrollable or grid-based AI recommendations with actions: Save, View, Start.
- HelpWidget
  - Mini-help or chat-like widget with link to full Help Page.
- Footer
  - Minimal footer area with links and support info.

Technical details:
- All data fetch results must be treated as data ?? [] and guarded with Array.isArray where applicable.
- Use useState([]) for all array-like state (e.g., studies, children, recommendations).
- Type definitions (TypeScript) for:
  - Child: { id: string; name: string; age: number; progress: number; streak: number; lastActive?: string }
  - Study: { id: string; title: string; updatedAt: string; status: 'saved' | 'completed' | 'in-progress' }
  - Recommendation: { id: string; topic: string; confidence: number; notes?: string }
  - UIState for loading and empty states.

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Framework/Toolkit: React (Vite/Next.js) with TypeScript.
- State management: Local component state with useState; lift to context/store if shared across pages is required.
- Accessibility: All interactive elements have keyboard focus and ARIA labels where helpful.
- Data safety:
  - All arrays are guarded: const studies = data ?? []; (or Array.isArray(data) ? data : [])
  - Guard every map/filter/reduce with (studies ?? []).map(...) or Array.isArray(studies) ? studies.map(...) : []
- UI components:
  - Card components with rounded corners (20–28px), soft shadows, and pastel backgrounds.
  - Buttons with pill shape and bold colors per design guidelines; primary action use full-filled style; secondary actions use outlined.
  - Badges/pills for categories and labels with rounded borders.
  - Progress charts: simple bar or circular progress representation using SVG or canvas; pastel fills with minimal gridlines.
- Layout and styling:
  - Use a responsive grid: 1 column on small viewports, up to 3 columns on larger screens.
  - Spacing: 16–24px padding, 8–12px gaps between elements; generous white space.
  - Typography: Rounded sans-serif with the specified weights; bold numerals for progress and counts.
- Data visualization:
  - Minimal charts; focus on legibility and alignment with color palette; ensure no hard requirements for third-party chart libraries unless preferred.
- API integration:
  - All data reads assumed to come from Supabase queries; when simulating, ensure response handling uses data ?? [] and validation checks:
    - const studies = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : []
- Interactions:
  - Quick Create CTA opens a study-creation modal/wizard.
  - Open/Duplicate/Share/Export actions wire to placeholder handlers with clear separation of concerns.
  - AI recommendations include a “Save” action that adds to Recent Studies; simulate with local state.
- Performance:
  - Use memoization for expensive renders if needed; avoid unnecessary re-renders through proper dependency arrays.

### Backend
- Since the prompt specifies no APIs connected, implement mock endpoints or local data services if required for UI preview:
  - Endpoints (optional): /api/dashboard/parents, /api/dashboard/children, /api/dashboard/recommendations
  - Data shape and contracts compatible with frontend types above.
- Data layer:
  - Implement repository patterns or hooks that return data shaped as described, with safety to return [] on empty results.

### Integration
- Data flow:
  - Dashboard component aggregates data from multiple sources: children, progress metrics, studies, recommendations.
  - Ensure all sources feed into the UI with proper guards:
    - const children = Array.isArray(data?.children) ? data.children : []
    - const studies = Array.isArray(data?.studies) ? data.studies : []
    - const recommendations = Array.isArray(data?.recommendations) ? data.recommendations : []
- Interaction wiring:
  - Quick Create triggers StudyWizard via context or prop callback.
  - Actions on studies update local state and, if implemented, trigger API calls with safe payloads.

## User Experience Flow
- Step 1: User lands on Dashboard after login. TopNav shows Create Study CTA.
- Step 2: ProgressOverviewGrid renders per-child progress cards. If no children, show a friendly empty-state prompt to add a child.
- Step 3: RecentStudiesList shows most recently saved studies; each item offers Open, Duplicate, Share, Export.
- Step 4: QuickCreateCard invites user to start a new study with two pathways: upload teacher materials or start from a template.
- Step 5: RecommendedStudiesCarousel displays AI-suggested topics; user can Save to add to their studies, or Start to open creation flow.
- Step 6: HelpWidget remains accessible; footer provides help links.
- Step 7: All actions provide visual feedback with hover/press states and accessible focus states.

## Technical Specifications

- Data Models:
  - Child: { id: string; name: string; age: number; progress: number; streak: number; lastActive?: string }
  - Study: { id: string; title: string; updatedAt: string; status: 'saved' | 'completed' | 'in-progress' }
  - Recommendation: { id: string; topic: string; confidence: number; notes?: string }
- API Endpoints (optional for integration):
  - GET /api/dashboard/children -> { data?: Child[] }
  - GET /api/dashboard/studies?limit=10 -> { data?: Study[] }
  - GET /api/dashboard/recommendations -> { data?: Recommendation[] }
  - POST /api/dashboard/studies (create new study)
- Security:
  - Ensure authentication is required for dashboard access; use session/auth tokens as per project standards.
  - Validate user authorization within backend endpoints; enforce that data accessed belongs to the authenticated user.
- Validation:
  - Ensure inputs are validated on create/update flows; use fallbacks to [] when data is missing.
  - Validate response shapes: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : []

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Dashboard renders with at least: one child progress card, at least one recent study, and one recommended study (or graceful empty-state prompts if none exist).
- [ ] All arrays used for rendering are guarded against null/undefined; use data ?? [] and Array.isArray checks where applicable.
- [ ] All React state initializations for arrays use proper defaults, e.g., useState<Child[]>([]), useState<Study[]>([]).
- [ ] Quick Create CTA opens the study creation flow; actions such as Open/Duplicate/Share/Export trigger corresponding handlers without runtime errors.
- [ ] UI adheres to the design system: rounded cards, pastel palette, responsive grid, accessible controls, and appropriate hover/active states.
- [ ] No runtime crashes due to null/undefined array operations; all maps/filters/reduces guarded as described.

## UI/UX Guidelines
Apply the project's design system:
- Use soft pastel peach, muted lavender, and bright tangerine as primary accents.
- Maintain off-white and very light peach backgrounds with gentle gradients.
- Headings in dark gray; supporting text in medium gray; data highlights in bold accent colors.
- Typography: Rounded geometric sans-serif; weights 400/500/700; bold numerals for stats.
- Spacing: Generous white space; 16–24px padding; 8–12px gaps.
- Card design: 20–28px border radius, soft shadows, light borders or none; hover/active states show elevation or glow.
- Navigation: Top nav with avatar; bottom navigation bar with rounded/pill shapes and active indicators.
- Data visualization: Rounded charts with pastel fills; minimal gridlines; clear callouts.
- Interactive elements: Pill-shaped buttons, micro-interactions, smooth transitions.

---

Generate the complete, detailed prompt now: for style.

CRITICAL DESIGN REQUIREMENTS:
- You MUST follow ALL design principles and patterns specified in the Design Reference above
- Do NOT deviate from the design specifications without explicit user permission
- Implement ALL visual design elements (colors, typography, spacing, shadows, animations) as specified
- Follow the layout patterns and component designs exactly as documented
- Ensure all interactions and micro-animations match the reference specifications

CRITICAL TECHNICAL REQUIREMENTS:
- React 18.3.1, React Router 6.30.1
- Tailwind CSS v3 with tailwind.config.js and custom keyframes
- @tailwindcss/typography plugin for rich text content
- Tailwind CSS animations (NOT Motion library or framer-motion)
- Sonner for toasts
- Recharts for data visualization
- Native fetch() with API utilities in src/lib/api.ts
- Design system with CSS custom properties
- Use RGB color values for theming
- When Supabase is configured: use Edge Functions for LLM and server-only logic; never expose API keys in the client

